  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial of Gratitude for the Imperial Rite Offered to the Deceased Minister
  author: Choe Yu-seon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    From the clouded heavens grace descends,
    And the path to the other realm gleams bright.
    Bowing in reverence, I return
    With grief and honor beyond measure.

    [The Central Section]

    Humbly I contemplate: Your Majesty,
    Who fathoms the mysteries of the divine
    And comprehends the transformation of all things,
    Grasping the wisdom of antiquity to govern the present,
    Covering all beneath your virtue and majesty,
    Spreading the realm to boundless horizons,
    Watering the land with benevolence and compassion
    Until all beneath heaven turn their hearts toward you.

    You grieve for my former lord's departure from this world,
    And compassionately mourn the lifelong sorrow of his heirs.
    Sending forth your envoy in person,
    You bestow upon us the sacred rite:
    All the offerings from the royal kitchen,
    All the treasures from the imperial treasury,
    Splendid honors extraordinary,
    Illuminating and adorning his wandering spirit.

    Looking up, I perceive your boundless grace,
    Yet how can my trembling heart find words?
    Bowing low, I can only vow
    To transform filial piety into loyal service—
    This alone remains my path of gratitude.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a formal memorial presented to the throne in response to the emperor's ceremonial offering to a deceased minister. The 'Middle Section' (中謝) marks a structural division in official memorials of this period.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of 'clouded heavens' descending grace reflects the cosmological understanding of imperial virtue flowing downward through the celestial hierarchy.
  - key: ''
    value: The final vow—transforming filial duty into loyalty to the throne—represents the Confucian ideal of how personal virtue extends outward to serve the state.
